tr:a43466cffeeda6e5:
A component re-renders when: **state changes**, **props change**, **consumed context changes**, or **parent re-renders** (by default, children re-render even if props are unchanged).

### Key point: re-render ≠ DOM update
Re-render is just React calling the component function to build a new VDOM. If the diff is identical, **the real DOM is not touched**. The expensive part is usually (1) heavy computation *inside* render, or (2) a large subtree re-rendering — not the function call itself.

```javascript
// ❌ Every time Parent renders, <Child> re-renders too
//    even though it uses nothing from Parent
function Parent() {
  const [count, setCount] = useState(0);
  return (
    <>
      <button onClick={() => setCount(c => c+1)}>{count}</button>
      <ExpensiveChild />  // re-renders on every click
    </>
  );
}

// ✅ Wrap with memo: Child only re-renders when its props change
const ExpensiveChild = React.memo(function() { ... });
```

<div class="pitfall"><span class="label">Senior mindset</span><p>Don't memoize blindly. <code>React.memo</code>/<code>useMemo</code>/<code>useCallback</code> all have costs (comparison + memory). Only optimize after <em>measuring</em> with React DevTools Profiler. "Premature optimization" makes code harder to read without making it faster — this is a hallmark that separates true seniors from those who just parrot advice.</p></div>

<div class="followup"><span class="label">Common follow-up</span><p>"How do you know which components are re-rendering unnecessarily?" — React DevTools Profiler, enable "Highlight updates", or use <code>why-did-you-render</code>. Seniors always <em>measure first, optimize later</em>.</p></div>

<div class="ladder"><span class="label">🪜 Deep dive ladder — interview yourself</span><p class="ladder-intro">Don't stop at definitions. Answer each question yourself before checking the sample answer — where you get stuck reveals your true depth.</p><ol class="ladder-list"><li class="lq-item"><div class="lq-row"><span class="ln">1</span><span class="lq-text">Why do children re-render by default when parent re-renders, even if props haven't changed? Could React behave differently?</span><button class="lq-toggle" data-target="lq-1-0" aria-expanded="false">Show answer</button></div><div class="lq-ans" id="lq-1-0" hidden=""><div class="lq-ans-inner">Because React is a pure UI library — it doesn't track dependencies like Vue or Svelte. The simplest way to ensure children are consistent with their parent is to re-render them when the parent changes. In practice, this is <em>rarely</em> expensive because re-render ≠ DOM update. React <em>could</em> behave differently, but that would be much more complex and rarely necessary.</div></div></li><li class="lq-item"><div class="lq-row"><span class="ln">2</span><span class="lq-text">If re-render doesn't touch the DOM, where does the 'cost' actually come from — what metric do you measure?</span><button class="lq-toggle" data-target="lq-1-1" aria-expanded="false">Show answer</button></div><div class="lq-ans" id="lq-1-1" hidden=""><div class="lq-ans-inner">Measure with <strong>React DevTools Profiler</strong>: look at the "flame graph", "ranked chart", and "why did this render". The real cost is: the milliseconds to re-run a heavy component function, or a deep subtree re-rendering many times within a single frame. The function call itself is usually lightweight, often under 1ms.</div></div></li><li class="lq-item"><div class="lq-row"><span class="ln">3</span><span class="lq-text">React Compiler (React 19) auto-memoizes. How does it change the advice 'don't memoize blindly'?</span><button class="lq-toggle" data-target="lq-1-2" aria-expanded="false">Show answer</button></div><div class="lq-ans" id="lq-1-2" hidden=""><div class="lq-ans-inner">React Compiler (React 19) automatically inserts memoization. The advice "don't memoize blindly" still holds in <em>spirit</em> — avoid manually complicating your code. But if you use the Compiler, it will memoize correctly without manual effort. For older codebases not using the Compiler, the old advice remains fully valid.</div></div></li><li class="lq-item"><div class="lq-row"><span class="ln">4</span><span class="lq-text">Why doesn't React just automatically wrap every component in memo?</span><button class="lq-toggle" data-target="lq-1-3" aria-expanded="false">Show answer</button></div><div class="lq-ans" id="lq-1-3" hidden=""><div class="lq-ans-inner">Because memoization has a cost: every render still requires a <strong>shallow comparison of old/new props</strong>. If a component is lightweight and re-renders frequently, the comparison cost can exceed the cost of re-rendering. React optimizes for the common case: re-rendering is cheap, so memo is opt-in, not default.</div></div></li><li class="lq-item"><div class="lq-row"><span class="ln">5</span><span class="lq-text">When would you INTENTIONALLY want a component to re-render even though its props haven't changed?</span><button class="lq-toggle" data-target="lq-1-4" aria-expanded="false">Show answer</button></div><div class="lq-ans" id="lq-1-4" hidden=""><div class="lq-ans-inner">When you want the component to react to changes outside props/state — for example: a component reading from an external store using <code>useSyncExternalStore</code>; or in special patterns like a "render controller" coordinating animations that need to render every frame. These are edge cases, but knowing them shows you understand the model.</div></div></li></ol></div>

tr:f24a8b8165edad4c:
A closure is when a function continues to access variables from the scope *where it was defined*, even after that scope has finished executing.

```javascript
// Function factory + "private" variables
function createCounter() {
  let count = 0;        // "in the backpack", inaccessible from outside
  return {
    inc: () => ++count,
    get: () => count,
  };
}
const c = createCounter();
c.inc(); c.inc();
c.get(); // 2  — count is "remembered" across calls
```

#### Real-world applications
- **Data privacy**: private variables via module pattern (as in the example above).
- **Function factory**: create pre-configured functions, e.g. `multiplyBy(2)`.
- **React Hooks**: `useState` preserves state across renders *thanks to* closures.
- **debounce/throttle**: holds `timerId` via closure.

<div class="pitfall"><span class="label">React connection</span><p>Understanding closures is key to understanding *stale closures* in useEffect. Senior interviews love connecting these two concepts. If you can explain both coherently, you score big points.</p></div>
<div class="ladder"><span class="label">🪜 Deep dive ladder — interview yourself</span><p class="ladder-intro">Don't stop at the definition. Answer each question before viewing the sample answer — where you get stuck is your real depth.</p><ol class="ladder-list"><li class="lq-item"><div class="lq-row"><span class="ln">1</span><span class="lq-text">Closures 'hold' variables — how does this affect memory (memory leaks)?</span><button class="lq-toggle" data-target="lq-6-0" aria-expanded="false">View answer</button></div><div class="lq-ans" id="lq-6-0" hidden=""><div class="lq-ans-inner">A closure holds a *reference* to the variable, not a copy. If the inner function holds a reference to a large object in the outer scope, that object cannot be garbage collected even after the outer scope finishes. Memory leaks occur when a closure is unintentionally kept alive longer than needed (e.g., event listeners not removed, unbounded caches).</div></div></li><li class="lq-item"><div class="lq-row"><span class="ln">2</span><span class="lq-text">Why is closure the foundation for useState preserving state across renders?</span><button class="lq-toggle" data-target="lq-6-1" aria-expanded="false">View answer</button></div><div class="lq-ans" id="lq-6-1" hidden=""><div class="lq-ans-inner">React stores state in an internal array indexed by hook call order. On each render, the component function re-runs and hooks access their correct slot. `useState` returns a tuple `[state, setter]` from that slot. The component function is a closure that captures the setter — so the setter always works even after the render finishes.</div></div></li><li class="lq-item"><div class="lq-row"><span class="ln">3</span><span class="lq-text">Module pattern uses closures for 'private' — how is ES2022 #private fields different?</span><button class="lq-toggle" data-target="lq-6-2" aria-expanded="false">View answer</button></div><div class="lq-ans" id="lq-6-2" hidden=""><div class="lq-ans-inner">ES2022 `#field` is truly private at the engine level — inaccessible from outside even via reflection or prototype. Closure "private" is only a convention — no one can access the variable inside the closure, but you can still accidentally expose it. `#field` is a language guarantee, closure is a pattern guarantee.</div></div></li><li class="lq-item"><div class="lq-row"><span class="ln">4</span><span class="lq-text">Closures in loops with var vs let — why are the results different?</span><button class="lq-toggle" data-target="lq-6-3" aria-expanded="false">View answer</button></div><div class="lq-ans" id="lq-6-3" hidden=""><div class="lq-ans-inner">With `var`, the loop has a single shared variable `i`. When the callback runs later, `i` is already the final value. With `let`, each iteration creates a *new binding* of `i` — each closure captures the correct value for that iteration. This is a consequence of block scope vs function scope.</div></div></li><li class="lq-item"><div class="lq-row"><span class="ln">5</span><span class="lq-text">When does a closure become a trap causing hard-to-find bugs in real code?</span><button class="lq-toggle" data-target="lq-6-4" aria-expanded="false">View answer</button></div><div class="lq-ans" id="lq-6-4" hidden=""><div class="lq-ans-inner">Examples: an event listener in useEffect without cleanup, where the closure captures stale component state; an unbounded cache function that holds large objects forever; an async callback created in an old context that runs after component unmount and calls setState — React warns about this.</div></div></li></ol></div>

tr:50a54791a611ba60:
A Promise is an object representing a value that *will exist in the future*, in one of three states: pending → fulfilled / rejected. `async/await` is a cleaner syntax for working with Promises, reading like sequential code.

```javascript
// ✅ try/catch catches errors for async/await
async function load() {
  try {
    const res = await fetch(url);
    if (!res.ok) throw new Error(res.status);
    return await res.json();
  } catch (e) {
    // log, fallback, or rethrow
  }
}

// Run CONCURRENTLY when tasks are independent:
const [a, b] = await Promise.all([getA(), getB()]);
```

<div class="pitfall"><span class="label">Performance Pitfall</span><p>Awaiting independent tasks sequentially doubles the time. Use <code>Promise.all</code> to run them concurrently. Seniors are often asked: "What's the difference between Promise.all vs allSettled vs race vs any?" — master all four.</p></div>
<div class="ladder"><span class="label">🪜 Deep Dive Ladder — Interview Yourself</span><p class="ladder-intro">Don't stop at definitions. Answer each question yourself before viewing the sample answer — where you get stuck reveals your true depth.</p><ol class="ladder-list"><li class="lq-item"><div class="lq-row"><span class="ln">1</span><span class="lq-text">Why was Promise introduced to replace callbacks — what is the real problem behind 'callback hell'?</span><button class="lq-toggle" data-target="lq-9-0" aria-expanded="false">View Answer</button></div><div class="lq-ans" id="lq-9-0" hidden=""><div class="lq-ans-inner">Callback hell isn't just about deep nesting — the deeper issues are: <em>no return value</em> (not composable), <em>inconsistent error handling</em> (who handles errors? passed as parameter or thrown?), and <em>inversion of control</em> (you hand over callbacks to a library, losing control over when/how many times they're called). Promise solves all three.</div></div></li><li class="lq-item"><div class="lq-row"><span class="ln">2</span><span class="lq-text">Promise.all fails fast when one rejects — when is this the WRONG behavior you want?</span><button class="lq-toggle" data-target="lq-9-1" aria-expanded="false">View Answer</button></div><div class="lq-ans" id="lq-9-1" hidden=""><div class="lq-ans-inner"><code>Promise.allSettled</code> waits for all even if some fail — use when operations are independent and you need results from <em>all</em> (e.g., sending multiple emails, batch API calls). <code>Promise.race</code> takes the first one — used for timeout patterns. <code>Promise.any</code> takes the first successful one — used when you have multiple fallback sources.</div></div></li><li class="lq-item"><div class="lq-row"><span class="ln">3</span><span class="lq-text">Sequential await vs parallel Promise.all — why do people accidentally write slow code?</span><button class="lq-toggle" data-target="lq-9-2" aria-expanded="false">View Answer</button></div><div class="lq-ans" id="lq-9-2" hidden=""><div class="lq-ans-inner">Because <code>await</code> looks <em>like synchronous code</em>, developers accidentally write sequential code when tasks are actually independent. Example: fetching user and fetching posts are two independent requests but often written as <code>await fetchUser(); await fetchPosts();</code> — total time = A + B instead of max(A,B). Rule: create all Promises first, then await them all via <code>Promise.all</code>.</div></div></li><li class="lq-item"><div class="lq-row"><span class="ln">4</span><span class="lq-text">What happens to an unhandled rejected Promise? Why is this dangerous?</span><button class="lq-toggle" data-target="lq-9-3" aria-expanded="false">View Answer</button></div><div class="lq-ans" id="lq-9-3" hidden=""><div class="lq-ans-inner">Unhandled rejection crashes the Node.js process (from Node 15+) or causes silent errors in the browser. In some browser versions, it fires the <code>unhandledrejection</code> event — which can be caught globally for logging. Seniors always have <code>try/catch</code> or <code>.catch()</code> coverage, plus a global error handler as the last line of defense.</div></div></li><li class="lq-item"><div class="lq-row"><span class="ln">5</span><span class="lq-text">What is the underlying relationship between async/await and generators?</span><button class="lq-toggle" data-target="lq-9-4" aria-expanded="false">View Answer</button></div><div class="lq-ans" id="lq-9-4" hidden=""><div class="lq-ans-inner"><code>async/await</code> is syntactic sugar over generators + Promises. Generators (<code>function*</code>) can pause (<code>yield</code>) and resume — this is the foundation. An <code>async</code> function is a special generator that is "auto-run" by a runner. Understanding this helps explain why <code>await</code> can only be used inside <code>async</code> functions, and how Babel transforms it.</div></div></li></ol></div>

