[{"question":"Design a compound Tabs component that allows users to customize the layout (e.g., placing the tab list at the top or bottom) while keeping the internal state management hidden. How would you implement it?","expectedPoints":["Uses React Context to share state (active tab) between Tabs, List, Trigger, Panel without prop drilling.","Exposes a compound API: <Tabs>, <Tabs.List>, <Tabs.Trigger>, <Tabs.Panel> with implicit state via context.","Allows layout customization by letting users reorder children or add wrappers, while state remains internal.","Handles accessibility (ARIA roles, keyboard navigation) and edge cases (no default tab, duplicate values)."],"followUps":["How would you handle the case where a user wants to render the tab list in a sidebar and the panels in a main area?","What if the user needs to control the active tab externally (controlled mode)?"],"difficulty":"senior","type":"system_design","childExplanation":"Imagine you have a set of toy blocks that snap together to make a castle. Each block is a separate piece, but they all share a secret rule about which tower is the main one. You can rearrange the blocks however you like, but the secret rule stays inside. That's what compound components do: they let you move pieces around while keeping the important information hidden inside.","detailedExplanation":"<p>The <strong>Compound Components pattern</strong> in React allows you to build a set of components that work together implicitly, sharing state via <strong>React Context</strong> without the consumer needing to pass props manually. This is ideal for complex UI widgets like tabs, accordions, or menus where the internal state (e.g., which tab is active) should be hidden from the user, but the layout should be fully customizable.</p><h4>How it works</h4><p>The parent component (e.g., <code>&lt;Tabs&gt;</code>) creates a context that holds the active value and a setter function. Child components like <code>&lt;Tabs.List&gt;</code>, <code>&lt;Tabs.Trigger&gt;</code>, and <code>&lt;Tabs.Panel&gt;</code> consume that context to read or update the state. The user composes them declaratively:</p><pre><code>&lt;Tabs defaultValue="profile"&gt;
  &lt;Tabs.List&gt;
    &lt;Tabs.Trigger value="profile"&gt;Profile&lt;/Tabs.Trigger&gt;
    &lt;Tabs.Trigger value="settings"&gt;Settings&lt;/Tabs.Trigger&gt;
  &lt;/Tabs.List&gt;
  &lt;Tabs.Panel value="profile"&gt;...&lt;/Tabs.Panel&gt;
  &lt;Tabs.Panel value="settings"&gt;...&lt;/Tabs.Panel&gt;
&lt;/Tabs&gt;</code></pre><p>Because state lives in context, the user can reorder children, add wrappers, or even split the list and panels across different parts of the DOM—the state remains connected.</p><h4>Why it matters in production</h4><p>This pattern solves the <strong>prop explosion problem</strong>: instead of passing dozens of props to a monolithic Tabs component, you let the user compose the UI freely. It also improves <strong>accessibility</strong> because you can embed ARIA attributes (e.g., <code>role="tablist"</code>, <code>aria-selected</code>) directly in the child components. Libraries like <strong>Reach UI</strong> and <strong>Radix UI</strong> use this pattern extensively.</p><h4>Common pitfall</h4><p>Over-engineering: not every component needs compound children. If the layout is fixed and the API is simple, a single component with a few props is easier to maintain. Also, beware of <strong>tight coupling</strong>—if children depend too much on the parent's context structure, changing the parent may break them. Always document the expected children and their required props.</p>"}]

