[{"question":"How would you decide between AVIF, WebP, and SVG for images on a high-traffic e-commerce product page?","expectedPoints":["Prioritizes AVIF for photos due to best compression and growing support.","Uses WebP as fallback for AVIF, noting ~30% size reduction over JPEG/PNG.","Selects SVG for icons/logos because of scalability and CSS styling.","Considers browser support and provides fallback chain (AVIF → WebP → JPEG/PNG).","Mentions trade-offs: AVIF encoding cost vs. bandwidth savings, SVG complexity for photos."],"followUps":["What would you do if a user's browser doesn't support AVIF or WebP?","How would you handle responsive images with these formats?"],"difficulty":"senior","type":"system_design","childExplanation":"Imagine you're packing toys for a trip. AVIF is like a super-squeezed bag that fits the most toys but only works with some suitcases. WebP is a smaller bag that works with more suitcases. SVG is like a magic drawing that never gets blurry, perfect for logos. You need to choose the best bag for each toy, and always have a backup bag just in case.","detailedExplanation":"<p>When designing a high-traffic e-commerce product page, image format selection directly impacts page load time, bandwidth costs, and user experience. The decision should balance <strong>compression efficiency</strong>, <strong>browser support</strong>, and <strong>image type</strong>.</p><h4>Format Prioritization</h4><ul><li><strong>AVIF</strong>: Best compression (up to 50% smaller than JPEG) with modern features like HDR and transparency. Use for product photos and backgrounds. However, encoding is computationally expensive, and support is still growing (Chrome, Firefox, Safari 16.4+).</li><li><strong>WebP</strong>: Excellent fallback with ~30% size reduction over JPEG/PNG. Supported in all modern browsers. Use as the primary format for most images when AVIF is not available.</li><li><strong>SVG</strong>: Ideal for icons, logos, and vector graphics. Resolution-independent, small file size, and stylable via CSS. Avoid for complex photographic content.</li><li><strong>JPEG/PNG</strong>: Universal fallback for legacy browsers. PNG for transparency, JPEG for photos.</li></ul><h4>Implementation Strategy</h4><p>Use the <code>&lt;picture&gt;</code> element with multiple <code>&lt;source&gt;</code> tags to serve AVIF first, then WebP, then JPEG/PNG. For example:</p><pre><code>&lt;picture&gt;
  &lt;source srcset="photo.avif" type="image/avif"&gt;
  &lt;source srcset="photo.webp" type="image/webp"&gt;
  &lt;img src="photo.jpg" alt="Product"&gt;
&lt;/picture&gt;</code></pre><h4>Production Considerations</h4><ul><li><strong>Responsive images</strong>: Combine format selection with <code>srcset</code> and <code>sizes</code> for different viewports.</li><li><strong>CDN and on-the-fly conversion</strong>: Services like Cloudinary or imgix can automatically serve the best format based on the user's browser.</li><li><strong>Common pitfall</strong>: Assuming all users support AVIF. Always provide fallbacks and test with real-world browser usage data.</li></ul>"}]

qgen_v2:80d36c16031a08d3:
[{"question":"How would you implement responsive images with lazy loading for a hero banner that should be the Largest Contentful Paint (LCP) element?","expectedPoints":["Avoid lazy loading for LCP images; use eager loading and fetchpriority='high'.","Use <picture> with multiple source elements for different formats (AVIF, WebP, fallback).","Specify explicit width and height (or aspect-ratio) to prevent layout shift (CLS).","Consider preloading the hero image via <link rel='preload'> for faster LCP.","Ensure the image is not lazy-loaded even if it appears below the fold in some viewports."],"followUps":["What if the hero image is below the fold on mobile but above the fold on desktop? How would you handle lazy loading?","How would you test whether lazy loading is hurting your LCP score?"],"difficulty":"senior","type":"conceptual","childExplanation":"Imagine you have a big picture at the top of a webpage. You want it to load quickly so people see it right away. If you tell the browser 'wait until you almost see it to load it' (lazy loading), it will be slow. So for the most important picture, you tell the browser 'load it now, it's important!' and also give it different formats so it picks the smallest one. You also set its width and height so the page doesn't jump around while loading.","detailedExplanation":"<p>When implementing responsive images with lazy loading for a hero banner that is the LCP element, the key principle is to <strong>never lazy-load the LCP image</strong>. Lazy loading (<code>loading='lazy'</code>) defers image loading until it is close to the viewport, which can significantly delay LCP. Instead, use <code>loading='eager'</code> (default) and add <code>fetchpriority='high'</code> to signal the browser to prioritize this resource.</p><h4>Responsive Image Markup</h4><p>Use the <code>&lt;picture&gt;</code> element to serve modern formats like AVIF and WebP with a fallback JPEG/PNG. This reduces file size without quality loss, improving load time. Example:</p><pre><code>&lt;picture&gt;
  &lt;source type='image/avif' srcset='hero.avif'&gt;
  &lt;source type='image/webp' srcset='hero.webp'&gt;
  &lt;img src='hero.jpg' width='1200' height='630' alt='Hero banner' fetchpriority='high'&gt;
&lt;/picture&gt;</code></pre><h4>Preventing Layout Shift (CLS)</h4><p>Always set explicit <code>width</code> and <code>height</code> attributes (or use <code>aspect-ratio</code> in CSS) so the browser reserves the correct space before the image loads. This avoids <strong>cumulative layout shift</strong>, a common performance issue.</p><h4>Preloading for LCP</h4><p>For the hero image, consider adding a <code>&lt;link rel='preload'&gt;</code> in the <code>&lt;head&gt;</code> to start the download even earlier. Example:</p><pre><code>&lt;link rel='preload' as='image' href='hero.avif' imagesrcset='hero.avif'&gt;</code></pre><h4>Common Pitfall</h4><p>A frequent mistake is applying lazy loading to all images indiscriminately, including the hero. This can degrade LCP by several seconds. Always audit which images are above the fold and ensure they are loaded eagerly.</p>"}]

