[{"question":"Implement a custom hook `useDebounce` that debounces a value by a given delay. Then use it in a search input that fetches results from an API when the user stops typing.","expectedPoints":["Correctly implements debounce logic with setTimeout and clearTimeout","Returns the debounced value after the delay","Uses the hook in a component with an input and API call (e.g., useEffect with debounced value)","Handles cleanup to avoid memory leaks and stale closures","Demonstrates understanding of dependency arrays and async patterns"],"followUps":["How would you modify this to debounce a function call instead of a value?","What are the trade-offs of using debounce vs throttle in this scenario?"],"difficulty":"senior","type":"conceptual","childExplanation":"Imagine you're playing a game where you press a button to shoot, but you only want to shoot once after you stop pressing quickly. Debounce is like waiting until you stop pressing for a moment, then shooting. In code, it waits until you stop typing for a bit before searching.","detailedExplanation":"<p>The <code>useDebounce</code> hook is a custom React hook that delays updating a value until after a specified delay has passed since the last change. It's commonly used to reduce the frequency of expensive operations like API calls or heavy computations triggered by user input.</p><h4>How It Works</h4><p>The hook uses <code>useState</code> to store the debounced value and <code>useEffect</code> to set a timer. When the input value changes, the effect clears any previous timer and sets a new one. After the delay, the timer callback updates the debounced state. The hook returns the debounced value, which can be used in a <code>useEffect</code> to trigger side effects like fetching data.</p><h4>Why It Matters in Production</h4><p>In fintech or SDK contexts, debouncing prevents unnecessary API calls, reducing server load and improving performance. For example, a search input that fetches results as the user types would otherwise fire a request on every keystroke, overwhelming the backend. Debouncing ensures requests are only made after the user pauses, providing a smoother experience.</p><h4>Common Pitfall</h4><p>A frequent mistake is forgetting to clean up the timer in the effect's cleanup function. Without cleanup, if the component unmounts or the value changes rapidly, the timer may still fire, leading to state updates on an unmounted component or stale closures. Always return a cleanup function that calls <code>clearTimeout</code>.</p><h4>Example Implementation</h4><pre><code>import { useState, useEffect } from 'react';

function useDebounce(value, delay) {
  const [debouncedValue, setDebouncedValue] = useState(value);

  useEffect(() => {
    const handler = setTimeout(() => {
      setDebouncedValue(value);
    }, delay);

    return () => {
      clearTimeout(handler);
    };
  }, [value, delay]);

  return debouncedValue;
}

export default useDebounce;</code></pre><p>Usage in a component:</p><pre><code>function SearchComponent() {
  const [query, setQuery] = useState('');
  const debouncedQuery = useDebounce(query, 500);

  useEffect(() => {
    if (debouncedQuery) {
      fetchResults(debouncedQuery);
    }
  }, [debouncedQuery]);

  return <input value={query} onChange={e => setQuery(e.target.value)} />;
}</code></pre>"}]

