console.log('D');","expectedPoints":["Correct order: A, D, C, B","Synchronous code (A, D) runs first on call stack","Promise.then is microtask, runs before macrotask (setTimeout)","setTimeout(0) is macrotask, runs after microtasks are drained","Microtask queue is emptied before next macrotask"],"followUps":["What if there were multiple microtasks? How would they be processed?","How would adding a second setTimeout(0) change the order?"],"difficulty":"senior","type":"conceptual","childExplanation":"Imagine you are doing homework (synchronous tasks). When you finish, you check your phone for urgent messages (microtasks like promises). Only after reading all urgent messages, you check your email (macrotasks like setTimeout). So 'A' and 'D' are homework, 'C' is urgent message, 'B' is email.","detailedExplanation":"<p>The JavaScript event loop processes tasks in a specific order: first all synchronous code on the <strong>call stack</strong>, then the <strong>microtask queue</strong> (which must be fully drained), then one <strong>macrotask</strong> from the macrotask queue, followed by a potential render step.</p><h4>Execution Order</h4><ul><li><code>console.log('A')</code> runs synchronously → logs 'A'.</li><li><code>setTimeout(..., 0)</code> schedules a macrotask (callback) into the macrotask queue.</li><li><code>Promise.resolve().then(...)</code> schedules a microtask into the microtask queue.</li><li><code>console.log('D')</code> runs synchronously → logs 'D'.</li><li>The call stack is now empty. The event loop checks the microtask queue first. It finds the promise callback and executes it → logs 'C'.</li><li>After the microtask queue is empty, the event loop picks the next macrotask (the setTimeout callback) and executes it → logs 'B'.</li></ul><h4>Why This Matters in Production</h4><p>Understanding this order is critical for debugging async code, especially when dealing with <strong>Promise</strong>-based APIs, <strong>queueMicrotask</strong>, or <strong>MutationObserver</strong>. A common pitfall is assuming <code>setTimeout(..., 0)</code> runs immediately after synchronous code, but microtasks always take precedence. This can lead to unexpected behavior if you rely on setTimeout to defer code after a promise resolution.</p><h4>Common Pitfall</h4><p>Developers often think <code>setTimeout(0)</code> is a way to defer execution to the end of the current script, but microtasks like <code>Promise.then</code> will always run before it. This can cause issues when mixing promise chains with timers, e.g., in testing or animation logic.</p>"}]

