[{"question":"Explain the difference between microtasks and macrotasks in the JavaScript event loop, and provide an example of how they are prioritized.","expectedPoints":["Defines microtasks (e.g., Promise callbacks, queueMicrotask) and macrotasks (e.g., setTimeout, setInterval, I/O).","States that microtasks are executed before macrotasks in each event loop iteration.","Provides a code example showing output order: synchronous code, then microtasks, then macrotasks.","Explains that the event loop processes all microtasks in a single cycle before moving to the next macrotask.","Mentions practical implications like UI blocking if microtasks are excessive."],"followUps":["What happens if a microtask queues another microtask?","How does requestAnimationFrame fit into the event loop?"],"difficulty":"mid","type":"conceptual","childExplanation":"Imagine you are cleaning your room. You have big tasks (like putting away clothes) and small tasks (like picking up a toy). The event loop is like you deciding to do all the small tasks first before starting a big task. This way, small things get done quickly and don't get stuck waiting.","detailedExplanation":"<p>The JavaScript event loop is a mechanism that coordinates the execution of code, processing events, and updating the UI. It distinguishes between two types of tasks: <strong>macrotasks</strong> and <strong>microtasks</strong>.</p><h4>Macrotasks</h4><p>Macrotasks include <code>setTimeout</code>, <code>setInterval</code>, <code>setImmediate</code>, I/O operations, and UI rendering events. They are queued in the macrotask queue and are processed one per event loop iteration.</p><h4>Microtasks</h4><p>Microtasks include <code>Promise.then</code>/<code>catch</code>/<code>finally</code>, <code>queueMicrotask</code>, and <code>MutationObserver</code> callbacks. They are queued in the microtask queue and are processed immediately after the currently executing script, before any macrotask.</p><h4>Execution Order</h4><p>In each event loop iteration:</p><ul><li>Execute one macrotask (e.g., a <code>setTimeout</code> callback).</li><li>Then, execute all microtasks in the queue (including any microtasks queued by other microtasks).</li><li>Then, perform UI rendering if needed.</li><li>Then, move to the next macrotask.</li></ul><p>For example:</p><pre><code>console.log('1');
setTimeout(() => console.log('2'), 0);
Promise.resolve().then(() => console.log('3'));
console.log('4');</code></pre><p>Output: <code>1 4 3 2</code>. The synchronous code runs first, then the microtask (Promise) runs before the macrotask (setTimeout).</p><h4>Why It Matters in Production</h4><p>Understanding this priority helps avoid performance pitfalls. For instance, queuing many microtasks in a loop can starve macrotasks, blocking UI updates. Conversely, using macrotasks for heavy computations can keep the UI responsive.</p><h4>Common Pitfall</h4><p>A common mistake is assuming <code>setTimeout(fn, 0)</code> runs immediately. It actually queues a macrotask, so it runs after all synchronous code and microtasks. This can lead to unexpected ordering if not accounted for.</p>","diagramMermaid":"flowchart TD
    A[Start] --> B[Execute Synchronous Code]
    B --> C{Microtask Queue Empty?}
    C -- No --> D[Process All Microtasks]
    D --> C
    C -- Yes --> E[Process One Macrotask]
    E --> F[UI Render if needed]
    F --> C"}]

