[{"question":"How does React decide whether to update, unmount, or skip a component during reconciliation?","expectedPoints":["Compares element type at same position in virtual DOM tree","Type change triggers unmount and remount, losing state","Same type with changed props triggers update, preserving state","Same type with unchanged props skips update entirely","Key prop helps identify elements in lists for stable reuse"],"followUps":["What happens if you define a component inside another component's render function?","Why is using array index as key problematic?"],"difficulty":"senior","type":"conceptual","childExplanation":"Imagine you have a toy box where each toy has a special spot. If you put a different toy in that spot, the old toy is thrown away and a new one appears. But if you just change the toy's hat (props), the toy stays and you just update the hat. React works like that: it checks if the type of element changed; if yes, it destroys the old and creates new; if no, it just updates the props. The 'key' is like a name tag so React can track toys even if they move spots.","detailedExplanation":"<p>React's reconciliation algorithm determines how to efficiently update the DOM when state or props change. The process begins by comparing the new virtual DOM tree with the previous one, starting from the root and moving down.</p><h4>Element Type Comparison</h4><p>At each position in the tree, React checks if the <strong>element type</strong> has changed. For example, changing from <code>&lt;div&gt;</code> to <code>&lt;span&gt;</code> or from <code>&lt;Foo&gt;</code> to <code>&lt;Bar&gt;</code> is considered a type change. If the type differs, React <strong>unmounts</strong> the existing component (destroying its state and cleaning up effects) and <strong>mounts</strong> a new one. This ensures a clean slate but can be expensive if unnecessary.</p><h4>Same Type Handling</h4><p>If the type is the same, React then checks if the <strong>props</strong> have changed. If props are unchanged, React <strong>skips the update</strong> entirely, reusing the existing instance without re-rendering. If props have changed, React updates the props on the same instance, preserving state and potentially re-running effects.</p><h4>Common Pitfall: Inline Component Definition</h4><p>A frequent mistake is defining a child component <strong>inside</strong> a parent's render function. This creates a new function reference every render, causing React to see a different element type each time. As a result, the child is unmounted and remounted on every parent render, losing its state. For example:</p><pre><code>function Parent() {
  const Child = () => &lt;div&gt;...&lt;/div&gt;;
  return &lt;Child /&gt;;
}</code></pre><p>This should be avoided by defining <code>Child</code> outside <code>Parent</code>.</p><h4>The Key Prop</h4><p>When rendering lists, the <code>key</code> prop helps React identify which items have changed, been added, or removed. Using <strong>stable, unique IDs</strong> (not array indices) prevents unnecessary remounts and preserves component state across reorders.</p>","diagramMermaid":"flowchart TD
    A[New Virtual DOM] --> B{Element type same?}
    B -- No --> C[Unmount + Remount]
    B -- Yes --> D{Props changed?}
    D -- No --> E[Skip update]
    D -- Yes --> F[Update props]
    C --> G[State lost]
    F --> H[State preserved]"}]

