[{"question":"When would you choose useReducer over useState in a React component?","expectedPoints":["State has multiple interdependent fields","Next state depends on previous state with complex logic","Multiple distinct actions update the state","Centralized update logic for testability","useReducer + Context as lightweight Redux alternative"],"followUps":["Can you give a concrete example where useReducer is clearly better than useState?","How would you test a reducer function in isolation?"],"difficulty":"senior","type":"conceptual","childExplanation":"Imagine you have a toy box where you need to add, remove, or reset toys. If you just have one toy, you can remember it easily (useState). But if you have many toys and rules (like 'add a car only if there's space'), it's better to write a list of instructions (useReducer) that tells you exactly what to do for each action.","detailedExplanation":"<p><strong>useReducer</strong> is a React hook for managing complex state logic. It is preferred over <strong>useState</strong> when the state involves multiple interdependent fields, when the next state depends on the previous state in non-trivial ways, or when there are many distinct actions that update the state.</p><h4>When to use useReducer</h4><ul><li><strong>Multiple interdependent fields</strong>: e.g., a form with amount, currency, and recipient – changing one may affect others.</li><li><strong>Complex state transitions</strong>: e.g., undo/redo, toggling with side effects, or state that depends on previous state via calculations.</li><li><strong>Many distinct actions</strong>: e.g., CRUD operations like <code>ADD</code>, <code>REMOVE</code>, <code>RESET</code>, <code>SUBMIT</code> – each action triggers a specific update.</li><li><strong>Testability</strong>: A reducer is a pure function that can be tested in isolation without rendering a component.</li></ul><h4>How it works</h4><p>You define a reducer function that takes the current state and an action, and returns the new state. Then you call <code>useReducer(reducer, initialState)</code> which returns the current state and a <code>dispatch</code> function. You call <code>dispatch({ type: 'ACTION_NAME', payload })</code> to trigger state updates.</p><h4>Why it matters in production</h4><p>Using <code>useReducer</code> centralizes state update logic, making it easier to reason about, debug, and test. It also avoids the complexity of multiple <code>useState</code> calls that might get out of sync. A common pitfall is overusing <code>useReducer</code> for simple state, adding unnecessary boilerplate. Stick to <code>useState</code> for independent, simple values.</p>","diagramMermaid":"flowchart TD
    A[Need state management] --> B{Multiple interdependent fields?}
    B -- Yes --> C{Next state depends on previous?}
    B -- No --> D[useState]
    C -- Yes --> E{Many distinct actions?}
    C -- No --> D
    E -- Yes --> F[useReducer]
    E -- No --> D
    F --> G[Pure reducer, testable]"}]

