[{"question":"How does event delegation work in the DOM, and what are its advantages over attaching individual event listeners?","expectedPoints":["Event delegation uses a single listener on a parent element to handle events from child elements via event bubbling.","It reduces memory usage by avoiding O(N) listeners.","It automatically handles dynamically added/removed child elements without rebinding.","It provides a single source of truth for event handling logic.","Common pitfall: using e.target instead of e.currentTarget or closest() to correctly identify the intended child."],"followUps":["How would you implement event delegation for a list where each item has a delete button?","What happens if a child element stops propagation? How does that affect delegation?"],"difficulty":"senior","type":"conceptual","childExplanation":"Imagine you have a big box of toys (the container) and you want to know when a child picks up a specific toy. Instead of putting a sensor on every toy (which is a lot of work and breaks if you add new toys), you put one sensor on the box. When a toy is picked, the box's sensor hears the noise and checks which toy it was. This way, you only need one sensor, and it works even for new toys you add later.","detailedExplanation":"<p><strong>Event delegation</strong> is a technique in the DOM where you attach a single event listener to a parent element to handle events that bubble up from its children. It leverages the <strong>event bubbling</strong> mechanism: when an event fires on a child, it propagates up through ancestors unless stopped.</p><h4>How it works</h4><p>Instead of adding a listener to each child (e.g., <code>items.forEach(item => item.addEventListener('click', handler))</code>), you add one listener to a common ancestor. Inside the handler, you use <code>e.target</code> or <code>e.target.closest(selector)</code> to determine which child triggered the event. For example:</p><pre><code>container.addEventListener('click', (e) => {
  const item = e.target.closest('[data-id]');
  if (item) handle(item);
});</code></pre><h4>Why it matters in production</h4><ul><li><strong>Performance</strong>: O(1) listener instead of O(N), reducing memory and setup time, especially for large lists.</li><li><strong>Dynamic content</strong>: Automatically handles elements added or removed after initial render, no need to rebind listeners.</li><li><strong>Maintainability</strong>: Single handler logic is easier to debug and update.</li></ul><h4>Common pitfall</h4><p>Using <code>e.target</code> directly without checking if it matches the desired child. For example, clicking a nested element inside an item (like a button inside a card) might give you the button, not the card. Always use <code>e.target.closest('.item')</code> to find the correct ancestor. Also, be aware that if a child calls <code>stopPropagation()</code>, the event won't reach the delegated listener.</p>","diagramMermaid":"flowchart LR
  A[Container Listener] -->|click event| B[Child 1]
  A -->|click event| C[Child 2]
  A -->|click event| D[Child 3]
  B -->|bubbles up| A
  C -->|bubbles up| A
  D -->|bubbles up| A
  subgraph Delegation
    A
  end"}]

