[{"question":"Explain why a stale closure occurs in useEffect and how to handle it.","expectedPoints":["Stale closure occurs when useEffect captures a value from a previous render due to closure over outdated variables.","Common cause: missing dependencies in the dependency array, causing the effect to use old values.","Solution: include all relevant variables in the dependency array to re-run the effect when they change.","Alternative: use useRef to hold mutable values that don't trigger re-renders, avoiding closure issues.","Using useCallback or useMemo with proper dependencies can also prevent stale closures in callbacks."],"followUps":["How would you fix a stale closure when using setInterval inside useEffect?","What happens if you omit the dependency array entirely?"],"difficulty":"senior","type":"conceptual","childExplanation":"Imagine you have a toy that remembers a number from yesterday, but today the number changed. The toy is stuck with the old number because it didn't get updated. In React, a stale closure is like that toy—it remembers an old value because the code didn't tell it to check for new values. To fix it, you make sure the code checks for the latest value every time it runs.","detailedExplanation":"<p>A <strong>stale closure</strong> in React's <code>useEffect</code> occurs when the effect's callback captures variables from an earlier render, leading to unexpected behavior because those variables are outdated. This happens because JavaScript closures close over the values at the time the function is created, not when it executes.</p><h4>How it works</h4><p>When a component re-renders, <code>useEffect</code> re-creates the effect function only if dependencies change. If you omit a variable from the dependency array, the effect will still reference the old value from the previous render. For example:</p><pre><code>const [count, setCount] = useState(0);
useEffect(() => {
  const timer = setInterval(() => {
    console.log(count); // always 0 if count not in deps
  }, 1000);
  return () => clearInterval(timer);
}, []);</code></pre><p>Here, <code>count</code> is captured as <code>0</code> and never updates.</p><h4>Why it matters in production</h4><p>Stale closures can cause bugs like outdated UI, incorrect API calls, or memory leaks. They are especially problematic in <strong>intervals</strong>, <strong>event listeners</strong>, or <strong>async operations</strong> where the effect runs once but needs fresh data.</p><h4>How to handle it</h4><ul><li><strong>Include all dependencies</strong>: Add every variable used inside the effect to the dependency array. This re-runs the effect when any dependency changes.</li><li><strong>Use <code>useRef</code></strong>: For values that change but shouldn't trigger re-runs, store them in a ref. The ref's <code>.current</code> property always holds the latest value without causing re-renders.</li><li><strong>Functional updates</strong>: For state setters, use the functional form (<code>setCount(prev => prev + 1)</code>) to avoid needing the state in deps.</li></ul><h4>Common pitfall</h4><p>Omitting the dependency array (<code>[]</code>) or incorrectly listing dependencies leads to stale closures. Always use linting rules (like <code>react-hooks/exhaustive-deps</code>) to catch missing deps.</p>","diagramMermaid":"flowchart LR
  A[Component Render] --> B[useEffect runs]
  B --> C{Captures variables}
  C -->|Deps unchanged| D[Stale closure]
  C -->|Deps updated| E[Fresh closure]
  D --> F[Uses old values]
  E --> G[Uses current values]
  F --> H[Bug]
  G --> I[Correct behavior]"}]

tr_v2:41f3920cdc100a1e:
JS is single-threaded. The event loop orchestrates: run the entire synchronous stack → drain the microtask queue → pick **one** macrotask → drain microtasks again → repeat (with rendering interspersed between cycles).

```javascript
console.log('1');
setTimeout(() => console.log('2'), 0);
Promise.resolve().then(() => console.log('3'));
console.log('4');
// Output: 1, 4, 3, 2
// synchronous (1,4) → microtask (3) → macrotask (2)
```

<div class="pitfall"><span class="label">Classic Question</span><p>For code mixing <code>console.log</code> + <code>setTimeout</code> + <code>Promise.then</code>, you must recite the order fluently. Note: <code>setTimeout(fn, 0)</code> does NOT run immediately — it is queued after all existing microtasks.</p></div>
<div class="followup"><span class="label">Follow-up</span><p>"What about an infinite microtask chain?" — It causes "starvation": permanently blocks rendering and macrotasks, freezing the page. This is why you should be careful with recursive Promises.</p></div>
<div class="ladder"><span class="label">🪜 Deep Dive Ladder — Interview Yourself</span><p class="ladder-intro">Don't stop at definitions. Answer each question yourself before viewing the sample answer — where you get stuck is your true depth.</p><ol class="ladder-list"><li class="lq-item"><div class="lq-row"><span class="ln">1</span><span class="lq-text">Why does JS choose the single-threaded + event loop model instead of multi-threading like Java?</span><button class="lq-toggle" data-target="lq-5-0" aria-expanded="false">View Answer</button></div><div class="lq-ans" id="lq-5-0" hidden=""><div class="lq-ans-inner">Multi-threading causes race conditions and deadlocks when sharing state — very hard to debug. Browsers need safe DOM manipulation from a single thread. The event loop + async model allows concurrency without locks. For I/O-bound tasks (network, disk) — which dominate the web — this model is extremely efficient.</div></div></li><li class="lq-item"><div class="lq-row"><span class="ln">2</span><span class="lq-text">Why are microtasks prioritized to drain completely before macrotasks — what problem does this design solve?</span><button class="lq-toggle" data-target="lq-5-1" aria-expanded="false">View Answer</button></div><div class="lq-ans" id="lq-5-1" hidden=""><div class="lq-ans-inner">Microtasks are created when an async operation completes (Promise). If they had to queue behind macrotasks, a chain of <code>.then().then()</code> would be interrupted by a setTimeout in between — breaking the atomicity of the chain. Prioritizing microtasks ensures a Promise chain runs continuously to completion before any other event can interject.</div></div></li><li class="lq-item"><div class="lq-row"><span class="ln">3</span><span class="lq-text">Where does requestAnimationFrame fit in the loop? Why is it different from setTimeout?</span><button class="lq-toggle" data-target="lq-5-2" aria-expanded="false">View Answer</button></div><div class="lq-ans" id="lq-5-2" hidden=""><div class="lq-ans-inner">rAF is scheduled before paint, after microtasks, but it is not a regular macrotask — it runs once per frame (~16ms). setTimeout(fn,0) can run multiple times between two frames or be coalesced. rAF syncs with the refresh rate → smooth animation; setTimeout does not guarantee that.</div></div></li><li class="lq-item"><div class="lq-row"><span class="ln">4</span><span class="lq-text">When does this model become a weakness — and how does Web Worker solve it?</span><button class="lq-toggle" data-target="lq-5-3" aria-expanded="false">View Answer</button></div><div class="lq-ans" id="lq-5-3" hidden=""><div class="lq-ans-inner">The main thread handles everything: JS, layout, paint, input. Heavy JS (large parsing, computation) blocks input → page freezes. Web Worker runs JS on a separate thread, cannot touch the DOM but communicates via messages. Suitable for: image processing, crypto, AI inference, parsing large files.</div></div></li><li class="lq-item"><div class="lq-row"><span class="ln">5</span><span class="lq-text">How many event loop cycles does await inside a for loop create? Why is it slow?</span><button class="lq-toggle" data-target="lq-5-4" aria-expanded="false">View Answer</button></div><div class="lq-ans" id="lq-5-4" hidden=""><div class="lq-ans-inner">Each <code>await</code> is a suspension point — the function returns, the event loop continues, then resumes when the Promise resolves. With sequential <code>for...of</code>, you create N consecutive yield points, each being one event loop cycle. <code>Promise.all</code> is better because all Promises are created immediately and run concurrently.</div></div></li></ol></div>

tr_v2:1ebd88e763062379:
A closure is a function that retains access to its lexical scope even when the function is executed outside that scope. In other words, it "remembers" the variables from where it was defined.

A practical real-world example: a counter function that increments a private variable without exposing it globally.

```javascript
function createCounter() {
  let count = 0;
  return function() {
    count++;
    return count;
  };
}

const counter = createCounter();
console.log(counter()); // 1
console.log(counter()); // 2
```

Another example: a function that fetches data with a specific ID, avoiding stale closure issues in asynchronous code.

```javascript
function fetchData(id) {
  return function() {
    fetch(`/api/data/${id}`)
      .then(response => response.json())
      .then(data => console.log(data));
  };
}

const fetchUser = fetchData(42);
fetchUser(); // Fetches data for ID 42
```

tr_v2:f24a8b8165edad4c:
A closure is when a function continues to access variables from the scope *where it was defined*, even after that scope has finished executing.

```javascript
// Function factory + "private" variable
function createCounter() {
  let count = 0;        // "in the backpack", inaccessible from outside
  return {
    inc: () => ++count,
    get: () => count,
  };
}
const c = createCounter();
c.inc(); c.inc();
c.get(); // 2  — count is "remembered" across calls
```

#### Real-world applications
- **Data privacy**: private variables via module pattern (as in the example above).
- **Function factory**: create pre-configured functions, e.g. `multiplyBy(2)`.
- **React Hooks**: `useState` preserves state across renders *thanks to* closure.
- **debounce/throttle**: holds `timerId` via closure.

<div class="pitfall"><span class="label">React connection</span><p>Understanding closure is key to understanding *stale closure* in useEffect. Senior interviews love connecting these two concepts. If you can explain both coherently, you score big points.</p></div>
<div class="ladder"><span class="label">🪜 Deep dive ladder — interview yourself</span><p class="ladder-intro">Don't stop at the definition. Answer each question before viewing the sample answer — where you get stuck is your real depth.</p><ol class="ladder-list"><li class="lq-item"><div class="lq-row"><span class="ln">1</span><span class="lq-text">Closure 'holds' variables — how does this affect memory (memory leaks)?</span><button class="lq-toggle" data-target="lq-6-0" aria-expanded="false">View answer</button></div><div class="lq-ans" id="lq-6-0" hidden=""><div class="lq-ans-inner">Closure holds a *reference* to the variable, not a copy. If the inner function holds a reference to a large object in the outer scope, that object cannot be garbage collected even after the outer scope finishes. Memory leaks occur when a closure is unintentionally kept alive longer than needed (e.g., event listener not removed, cache without limits).</div></div></li><li class="lq-item"><div class="lq-row"><span class="ln">2</span><span class="lq-text">Why is closure the foundation for useState preserving state across renders?</span><button class="lq-toggle" data-target="lq-6-1" aria-expanded="false">View answer</button></div><div class="lq-ans" id="lq-6-1" hidden=""><div class="lq-ans-inner">React stores state in an internal array indexed by hook call order. On each render, the component function re-runs and hooks access their correct slot. `useState` returns a tuple `[state, setter]` from that slot. The component function is a closure that captures the setter — so the setter always works even after the render finishes.</div></div></li><li class="lq-item"><div class="lq-row"><span class="ln">3</span><span class="lq-text">Module pattern uses closure for 'private' — how is ES2022 #private fields different?</span><button class="lq-toggle" data-target="lq-6-2" aria-expanded="false">View answer</button></div><div class="lq-ans" id="lq-6-2" hidden=""><div class="lq-ans-inner">ES2022 `#field` is truly private at the engine level — inaccessible from outside even via reflection or prototype. Closure "private" is only a convention — no one can access the variable inside the closure, but you can still accidentally expose it. `#field` is a language guarantee, closure is a pattern guarantee.</div></div></li><li class="lq-item"><div class="lq-row"><span class="ln">4</span><span class="lq-text">Closure in loops with var vs let — why are the results different?</span><button class="lq-toggle" data-target="lq-6-3" aria-expanded="false">View answer</button></div><div class="lq-ans" id="lq-6-3" hidden=""><div class="lq-ans-inner">With `var`, the loop has a single shared variable `i`. When the callback runs later, `i` is already the final value. With `let`, each iteration creates a *new binding* of `i` — each closure captures the exact value of that iteration. This is a consequence of block scope vs function scope.</div></div></li><li class="lq-item"><div class="lq-row"><span class="ln">5</span><span class="lq-text">When does closure become a trap causing hard-to-find bugs in real code?</span><button class="lq-toggle" data-target="lq-6-4" aria-expanded="false">View answer</button></div><div class="lq-ans" id="lq-6-4" hidden=""><div class="lq-ans-inner">Example: event listener in useEffect without cleanup, closure capturing old component state; cache function without size limits holding large objects forever; async callback created in an old context running after component unmount and calling setState — React warns about this.</div></div></li></ol></div>

