[{"question":"Explain the differences between debounce and throttle, and when to use each. Provide code examples.","expectedPoints":["Debounce delays execution until after a pause in events; throttle limits execution to once per interval.","Debounce is useful for search input or auto-save; throttle is useful for scroll or resize events.","Code example shows debounce clearing timeout on each call; throttle uses timestamp or flag.","Common pitfall: using debounce for continuous events like scrolling can cause lag; throttle is better.","Understanding of leading vs trailing edge execution in both patterns."],"followUps":["How would you implement a debounce function with leading edge execution?","Can you think of a scenario where you might want to use both debounce and throttle together?"],"difficulty":"mid","type":"conceptual","childExplanation":"Imagine you're playing a video game where you have to press a button to shoot. If you press it really fast, debounce would only shoot once after you stop pressing, while throttle would shoot at a steady rate no matter how fast you press. Debounce is like waiting for a pause, throttle is like a speed limit.","detailedExplanation":"<p><strong>Debounce</strong> and <strong>throttle</strong> are two techniques used to control how often a function is executed in response to frequent events (like typing, scrolling, or resizing). They help improve performance and prevent unnecessary computations.</p><h4>Debounce</h4><p>Debounce ensures that a function is called only after a specified amount of time has passed since the last event. If the event occurs again before that time, the timer resets. This is useful for scenarios like <strong>search input</strong> where you want to wait until the user stops typing before sending an API request, or <strong>auto-save</strong> in a form.</p><pre><code>function debounce(func, delay) {
  let timeout;
  return function(...args) {
    clearTimeout(timeout);
    timeout = setTimeout(() => func.apply(this, args), delay);
  };
}</code></pre><h4>Throttle</h4><p>Throttle ensures that a function is called at most once in a specified time interval. It ignores subsequent calls until the interval has passed. This is ideal for <strong>scroll events</strong>, <strong>resize events</strong>, or any continuous action where you want to limit the rate of execution.</p><pre><code>function throttle(func, limit) {
  let inThrottle;
  return function(...args) {
    if (!inThrottle) {
      func.apply(this, args);
      inThrottle = true;
      setTimeout(() => inThrottle = false, limit);
    }
  };
}</code></pre><h4>When to Use Which</h4><ul><li><strong>Debounce</strong>: Use when you want to wait for a pause (e.g., search suggestions, auto-save).</li><li><strong>Throttle</strong>: Use when you want to ensure a steady rate (e.g., scroll-based animations, infinite scroll).</li></ul><h4>Common Pitfall</h4><p>A common mistake is using debounce for continuous events like scrolling. This can cause the function to never execute if the user keeps scrolling, leading to a poor user experience. Throttle is the correct choice for such cases.</p>","diagramMermaid":"flowchart LR
