r v6) or <code>useRouter</code> (Next.js). When the user changes a filter, you update the URL via <code>setSearchParams</code> or <code>router.push</code>. The component re-renders based on the new URL, and the data fetching logic (e.g., React Query) uses these params as query keys.</p><h4>Why It Matters in Production</h4><p>Using URL state for filters ensures that users can bookmark or share a specific view. It also makes the app more robust—refreshing the page doesn't lose the user's context. This pattern is common in e-commerce, dashboards, and search pages.</p><h4>Common Pitfall</h4><p>One mistake is storing <strong>complex objects</strong> (e.g., nested ranges) directly in the URL without proper serialization. URLs have length limits (around 2000 characters), so you must encode efficiently (e.g., using <code>JSON.stringify</code> and <code>encodeURIComponent</code>). Another pitfall is forgetting to sync the URL with the actual filter state, leading to inconsistencies.</p>","diagramMermaid":"flowchart TD
